{"title_page": "Arthur Edwin Preston", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name                 = Arthur Edwin Preston\n|image                = \n|image_size           = \n|caption              = \n|nationality          = \n|birth_date           = {{Birth date|1852|10|1|df=yes}}\n|birth_place          = [[Abingdon-on-Thames]]\n|death_date           = {{Death date and age|1942|5|21|1852|10|1|df=yes}}\n|death_place          = [[Abingdon-on-Thames]]\n}}\n\n'''Arthur Edwin Preston''' (1852-1942) was the Mayor of [[Abingdon-on-Thames]], Master of [[Christ's Hospital of Abingdon|Christ's Hospital]] and an antiquarian and historian.<ref name=gov>{{cite web|url=http://www.abingdon.gov.uk/history/people/arthur-edwin-preston|title=Biography|publisher=abingdon.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Early years and education==\nSon of John (saddler, coach proprietor and tax collector) and Frances Preston (n\u00e9e Prince), he was born in Abingdon on 1 January 1852, at 13 High Street, next to the old Lion Hotel.<ref name=OBP>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfordshireblueplaques.org.uk/plaques/preston.html|title=Arthur Edwin PRESTON (1852\u20131942) Mayor, antiquarian, and historian of Abingdon|publisher=Oxfordshire Blue Plaques}}</ref>\n\nHe was educated at [[John Roysse]]'s [[Free school (England)|Free School]] in [[Abingdon-on-Thames]] (now [[Abingdon School]]) from 1861-1867. He gained a [[Bachelor of Arts]] at [[University of London|London University]] and became a fellow in 1882.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/63objects/object_48_waste_court|title=Object 48: Waste Court|publisher=Abingdon School}}</ref><ref name=obit/>\n\n==Career==\nBefore he attended University he had started to train as an accountant and was employed as a clerk. After University he became a chartered accountant and later became Borough Accountant of Abingdon.<ref name=OBP/> In 1887 he was called to the Bar at [[Gray's Inn]]. In 1891, he lived at the home of his widowed mother at Piccadilly House in Ock Street before marrying Lydia Jacobs of Burford in October 1895.<ref name=OBP/> He was the master of Abbey Lodge in 1893.\n\nThe couple purchased Whitefield in 1896 (14 Albert Park) at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/uploads/school/files/abingdonian/2010_V024_N005.pdf#page=17|title=Common Room Farewells|publisher=The Abingdonian}}</ref> The property today is the used as a health and medical centre for Abingdon School. He continued his career as a Chartered Accountant and Barrister at Law and was a founder member of the Institute of Chartered Accountants. He was the Borough Council accountant for twenty-two years.<ref name=gov/> He became a governor of Abingdon School from 1902-1942 and was Chairman of the Governors from 1937-1939 and a life Governor of Christ's Hospital in 1909.<ref name=obit>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/uploads/school/files/abingdonian/1942_Summer_V008_N004.pdf#page=19|title=Obituary|publisher=The Abingdonian}}</ref>\n\n==Public Service==\nHe retired in 1908 and devoted his later years to public service. He was elected to Berkshire County Council in 1895 and in 1909 served three years as Mayor of Abingdon.<ref name=OBP/> He was Chairman of the County Council Finance Committee and a county magistrate.<ref name=gov/> He was an Alderman of both County and Borough councils and on the Thames Conservancy Board and was made an Honorary Freeman in 1932.<ref name=OBP/> In 1922, he financed a major archaeological project in regard to the demolished 1538 Abbey church and in 1928 helped securing Waste Court for Abingdon School, where he remained as a Governor for the rest of his life and was Chairman from 1937-1939. In 1935, he financed a major ceiling restoration in the St Helens' Lady Chapel.<ref name=gov/><ref name=obit/>\n\n==Historian and Author==\nHe dedicated much of his time into researching the history of Abingdon and built up a large collection of documents and employing staff to transcribe and translate documents. He wrote several historical books including the '''St Nicholas Abingdon and Other Papers''' published in 1929, which covers the history of St Nicholas' Church, Abingdon School, and Fitzharris Manor.\n\nHe continued to finance Abingdon projects including the refurbishment of the Guildhall and [[John Roysse|Roysse Room]] (the original schoolroom of Abingdon School). He also helped restore Albert Park and founded the Abingdon Bowling Club and was co-founder of the Frilford Heath Golf Club.<ref name=gov/> <ref name=OBP/> He was also a President of the [[List of Old Abingdonians|Old Abingdonian Club]].<ref name=obit/>\n\n==Death==\nPreston died in 1942 while still residing at Whitefield, his wife Lydia died one year later.<ref name=obit/>\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | before=Harry Septimus Challenor | title=Mayor of Abingdon | years=1909-12 | after=William Legge }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Old Abingdonians]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Preston, Arthur Edwin}}\n[[Category:1852 births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of Berkshire County Council]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Oxfordshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Abingdon School]]\n[[Category:Governors of Abingdon School]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name                 = Arthur Edwin Preston\n|image                = \n|image_size           = \n|caption              = \n|nationality          = \n|birth_date           = {{Birth date|1852|10|1|df=yes}}\n|birth_place          = [[Abingdon-on-Thames]]\n|death_date           = {{Death date and age|1942|5|21|1852|10|1|df=yes}}\n|death_place          = [[Abingdon-on-Thames]]\n}}\n\n'''Arthur Edwin Preston''' (1852-1942) was the Mayor of [[Abingdon-on-Thames]], Master of [[Christ's Hospital of Abingdon|Christ's Hospital]] and an antiquarian and historian.<ref name=gov>{{cite web|url=http://www.abingdon.gov.uk/history/people/arthur-edwin-preston|title=Biography|publisher=abingdon.gov.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Early years and education==\nSon of John (saddler, coach proprietor and tax collector) and Frances Preston (n\u00e9e Prince), he was born in Abingdon on 1 January 1852, at 13 High Street, next to the old Lion Hotel.<ref name=OBP>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfordshireblueplaques.org.uk/plaques/preston.html|title=Arthur Edwin PRESTON (1852\u20131942) Mayor, antiquarian, and historian of Abingdon|publisher=Oxfordshire Blue Plaques}}</ref>\n\nHe was educated at [[John Roysse]]'s [[Free school (England)|Free School]] in [[Abingdon-on-Thames]] (now [[Abingdon School]]) from 1861-1867. He gained a [[Bachelor of Arts]] at [[University of London|London University]] and became a fellow in 1882.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/63objects/object_48_waste_court|title=Object 48: Waste Court|publisher=Abingdon School}}</ref> <ref name=obit/>\n\n==Career==\nBefore he attended University he had started to train as an accountant and was employed as a clerk. After University he became a chartered accountant and later became Borough Accountant of Abingdon.<ref name=OBP/> In 1887 he was called to the Bar at [[Gray's Inn]]. In 1891, he lived at the home of his widowed mother at Piccadilly House in Ock Street before marrying Lydia Jacobs of Burford in October 1895.<ref name=OBP/> He was the master of Abbey Lodge in 1893.\n\nThe couple purchased Whitefield in 1896 (14 Albert Park) at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/uploads/school/files/abingdonian/2010_V024_N005.pdf#page=17|title=Common Room Farewells|publisher=The Abingdonian}}</ref> The property today is the used as a health and medical centre for Abingdon School. He continued his career as a Chartered Accountant and Barrister at Law and was a founder member of the Institute of Chartered Accountants. He was the Borough Council accountant for twenty-two years.<ref name=gov/> He became a governor of Abingdon School from 1902-1942 and was Chairman of the Governors from 1937-1939 and a life Governor of Christ's Hospital in 1909.<ref name=obit>{{cite web|url=https://www.abingdon.org.uk/uploads/school/files/abingdonian/1942_Summer_V008_N004.pdf#page=19|title=Obituary|publisher=The Abingdonian}}</ref>\n\n==Public Service==\nHe retired in 1908 and devoted his later years to public service. He was elected to Berkshire County Council in 1895 and in 1909 served three years as Mayor of Abingdon.<ref name=OBP/> He was Chairman of the County Council Finance Committee and a county magistrate.<ref name=gov/> He was an Alderman of both County and Borough councils and on the Thames Conservancy Board and was made an Honorary Freeman in 1932.<ref name=OBP/> In 1922, he financed a major archaeological project in regard to the demolished 1538 Abbey church and in 1928 helped securing Waste Court for Abingdon School, where he remained as a Governor for the rest of his life and was Chairman from 1937-1939. In 1935, he financed a major ceiling restoration in the St Helens' Lady Chapel.<ref name=gov/> <ref name=obit/>\n\n==Historian and Author==\nHe dedicated much of his time into researching the history of Abingdon and built up a large collection of documents and employing staff to transcribe and translate documents. He wrote several historical books including the '''St Nicholas Abingdon and Other Papers''' published in 1929, which covers the history of St Nicholas' Church, Abingdon School, and Fitzharris Manor.\n\nHe continued to finance Abingdon projects including the refurbishment of the Guildhall and [[John Roysse|Roysse Room]] (the original schoolroom of Abingdon School). He also helped restore Albert Park and founded the Abingdon Bowling Club and was co-founder of the Frilford Heath Golf Club.<ref name=gov/> <ref name=OBP/> He was also a President of the [[List of Old Abingdonians|Old Abingdonian Club]].<ref name=obit/>\n\n==Death==\nPreston died in 1942 while still residing at Whitefield, his wife Lydia died one year later.<ref name=obit/>\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box |